  "news_story": "The immigration minister, Brandon Lewis, has assured the House of Commons home affairs select committee that the processing of settled status applications for EU nationals in Britain should take no more than a couple of weeks starting from the second half of the next year. To manage an estimated 3.5 million applications over the next two and a half years, the government is recruiting 1,200 more UK visa and immigration staff, bringing the total to around 7,700 employees. During his appearance before MPs, Lewis expressed optimism about reaching an agreement in the Brexit negotiations on the rights of EU citizens in the UK by Christmas, although he refrained from commenting onreports about the European Court of Justice (ECJ) having a continuing role in ensuring their rights during the transition period following the Brexit decision. Notably, he revealed that individuals refused settled status and classified as non-EU nationals in Britain illegally may have their bank accounts frozen and face deportation before any appeal is heard in British courts.The 3million group, a body representing EU nationals living in the UK, questioned Lewis’s assertion about making progress on the agreement by Christmas. They pointed out significant hindrances, including disagreements over the ECJ’s role and concerns about family reunification rights, as well as uncertainty regarding whether they will be exempted from what they called the ‘hostile environment measures.’ Yvette Cooper, chair of the Commons home affairs committee, was also doubtful that an increase of 1,200 staff, with already 700 recruited, would resolve the backlog faced by the UK Visas and Immigration agency currently handling 3 million applications a year with 6,500 staff. The challenge of reducing a current three-month delay in processing EU nationals' applications for permanent residence documents was highlighted."
}

